{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01NBfx2gKnUwcdjuMDby5zUX","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01SkHJyVBnkKDYhWZqamR7d9","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/tmp/temporal-worktrees/task-decomp-test-002-question-child-5/.fleet/tasks/decomp-test-002-question-child-5/research.json"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":7556,"cache_read_input_tokens":11325,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":7556},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"60a8e24c-a644-4c11-a7a3-4ffad872168e","uuid":"95328789-648f-4e41-863f-f2035645d78d"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VHPz4Y3KokBLVSyw1bENU4","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t{\n2\t  \"phase\": \"question\",\n3\t  \"questions\": [\n4\t    {\n5\t      \"id\": \"q1\",\n6\t      \"question\": \"Should node position changes be undoable even though the graph currently uses a static circular layout with no drag support? Do we need to implement drag-to-reposition first, or is the undo/redo system only for future position editing?\",\n7\t      \"category\": \"requirements\",\n8\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"BayesNetGraph.tsx computes positions via layoutNodes() with no user interaction. If there's no way to change positions yet, building undo for position changes is premature unless drag support is also in scope.\"\n9\t    },\n10\t    {\n11\t      \"id\": \"q2\",\n12\t      \"question\": \"For CPT probability edits, the current flow submits directly to the backend via useProbabilityEdit(). The task says 'before server submission' — should the undo/redo system intercept edits and batch them locally before a manual submit, or should it track already-submitted edits and reverse them with compensating API calls?\",\n13\t      \"category\": \"requirements\",\n14\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"This fundamentally changes the architecture. A local-only buffer requires a new 'draft/commit' flow in ConditionalEditor and VariableRow. Tracking submitted edits means the scope overlaps with server mutations despite the task saying 'server mutations are not reversible'.\"\n15\t    },\n16\t    {\n17\t      \"id\": \"q3\",\n18\t      \"question\": \"What constitutes a 'layout change' that should be undoable? The current layout is auto-computed (circular/grid). Does this refer to switching between layout algorithms, or manual node repositioning, or zoom/pan state?\",\n19\t      \"category\": \"requirements\",\n20\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"The scope of 'layout changes' is ambiguous. Each interpretation requires different command types and state tracking.\"\n21\t    },\n22\t    {\n23\t      \"id\": \"q4\",\n24\t      \"question\": \"Should the undo history persist across page navigations (e.g., leaving MarketDetail and returning), or is it ephemeral per component mount?\",\n25\t      \"category\": \"design\",\n26\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"Persistent history would require serialization to localStorage or session storage. Ephemeral history is simpler but users lose undo ability on navigation. This affects where HistoryContext is placed in the component tree.\"\n27\t    },\n28\t    {\n29\t      \"id\": \"q5\",\n30\t      \"question\": \"Should evidence toggle (assumption add/remove) undo restore the exact previous assumption state, or just remove the last assumption? AssumptionContext.addAssumption() replaces any existing assumption on the same variable.\",\n31\t      \"category\": \"design\",\n32\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"If a user assumes outcome A, then assumes outcome B on the same variable, undoing should restore A (not just clear B). This requires capturing the previous state in the command, not just the action type.\"\n33\t    },\n34\t    {\n35\t      \"id\": \"q6\",\n36\t      \"question\": \"Should undo/redo be scoped per-market (one history stack per MarketDetail) or global across the app?\",\n37\t      \"category\": \"design\",\n38\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"The AssumptionProvider is scoped to MarketDetail. If HistoryContext is also scoped there, each market gets its own stack. A global stack would need to track which market each action belongs to and handle cross-market interactions.\"\n39\t    },\n40\t    {\n41\t      \"id\": \"q7\",\n42\t      \"question\": \"Is there a maximum history depth, or should the stack grow unbounded?\",\n43\t      \"category\": \"design\",\n44\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"Unbounded history can consume significant memory, especially if commands store full state snapshots. A cap (e.g., 50 actions) keeps memory predictable and is standard UX.\"\n45\t    },\n46\t    {\n47\t      \"id\": \"q8\",\n48\t      \"question\": \"Where should the toolbar buttons be placed? There's no existing graph toolbar component. Should they go in the MarketDetail header area, inline with BayesNetGraph, or as a floating overlay?\",\n49\t      \"category\": \"codebase\",\n50\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"MarketDetail currently has no toolbar section. The placement decision affects component hierarchy and whether a new GraphToolbar component is needed or if buttons integrate into an existing section.\"\n51\t    },\n52\t    {\n53\t      \"id\": \"q9\",\n54\t      \"question\": \"Should Ctrl+Z/Ctrl+Shift+Z be active globally or only when the graph/market view is focused? The app has text inputs (account ID, agent ID, probability sliders) where Ctrl+Z has native browser meaning.\",\n55\t      \"category\": \"design\",\n56\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"Intercepting Ctrl+Z globally would break native undo in text inputs. The keyboard handler needs to distinguish between graph context and form input context to avoid hijacking browser behavior.\"\n57\t    },\n58\t    {\n59\t      \"id\": \"q10\",\n60\t      \"question\": \"Should grouped/compound actions (e.g., editing multiple probabilities in ConditionalEditor with context conditions) be undone as a single unit or individually?\",\n61\t      \"category\": \"design\",\n62\t      \"why_it_matters\": \"ConditionalEditor can submit an edit with multiple context conditions. If these are treated as atomic, one undo reverts everything. If granular, the user can partially undo which may leave the CPT in an inconsistent state.\"\n63\t    }\n64\t  ],\n65\t  \"assumptions\": [\n66\t    {\n67\t      \"id\": \"a1\",\n68\t      \"assumption\": \"The undo/redo system uses the command pattern with execute/undo method pairs on each command object, rather than full state snapshots\",\n69\t      \"confidence\": 0.85,\n70\t      \"if_wrong\": \"State snapshot approach (e.g., using immer patches) would simplify implementation but increase memory usage and change the core data structure design\"\n71\t    },\n72\t    {\n73\t      \"id\": \"a2\",\n74\t      \"assumption\": \"HistoryContext will be placed inside AssumptionProvider at the MarketDetail level, scoped per-market\",\n75\t      \"confidence\": 0.8,\n76\t      \"if_wrong\": \"A global history context would need to wrap the entire app in providers.tsx and track market IDs per action\"\n77\t    },\n78\t    {\n79\t      \"id\": \"a3\",\n80\t      \"assumption\": \"Keyboard shortcuts should only fire when focus is not inside a text input, textarea, or contenteditable element\",\n81\t      \"confidence\": 0.9,\n82\t      \"if_wrong\": \"If shortcuts should always fire, native browser undo in form fields would break, causing a degraded editing experience\"\n83\t    },\n84\t    {\n85\t      \"id\": \"a4\",\n86\t      \"assumption\": \"Evidence toggle undo means restoring the previous assumption state for that variable (not just clearing the current one)\",\n87\t      \"confidence\": 0.75,\n88\t      \"if_wrong\": \"Simpler implementation possible if undo just clears the assumption, but less useful UX\"\n89\t    },\n90\t    {\n91\t      \"id\": \"a5\",\n92\t      \"assumption\": \"Node position changes and layout changes refer to future capabilities that need stub commands, since the graph is currently static with no user-driven positioning\",\n93\t      \"confidence\": 0.6,\n94\t      \"if_wrong\": \"If drag-to-reposition is expected to ship alongside undo/redo, the scope is significantly larger than described\"\n95\t    },\n96\t    {\n97\t      \"id\": \"a6\",\n98\t      \"assumption\": \"History is ephemeral (cleared on unmount/navigation), not persisted to localStorage\",\n99\t      \"confidence\": 0.7,\n100\t      \"if_wrong\": \"Would need serialization/deserialization of command objects and localStorage management\"\n101\t    },\n102\t    {\n103\t      \"id\": \"a7\",\n104\t      \"assumption\": \"A reasonable max history depth of 50 actions will be used\",\n105\t      \"confidence\": 0.65,\n106\t      \"if_wrong\": \"Unbounded history could cause memory issues; very small cap could frustrate power users\"\n107\t    },\n108\t    {\n109\t      \"id\": \"a8\",\n110\t      \"assumption\": \"No new dependencies (like immer or zustand) need to be added — implementation uses React Context + useReducer\",\n111\t      \"confidence\": 0.8,\n112\t      \"if_wrong\": \"Adding a state management library would change the architectural approach and require dependency approval\"\n113\t    }\n114\t  ],\n115\t  \"spawn_children\": false,\n116\t  \"children\": []\n117\t}\n118\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"60a8e24c-a644-4c11-a7a3-4ffad872168e","uuid":"429f90e3-f162-4969-b965-d4b29f5d57e2","timestamp":"2026-04-11T21:48:50.772Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/tmp/temporal-worktrees/task-decomp-test-002-question-child-5/.fleet/tasks/decomp-test-002-question-child-5/questions.json","content":"{\n  \"phase\": \"question\",\n  \"questions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q1\",\n      \"question\": \"Should node position changes be undoable even though the graph currently uses a static circular layout with no drag support? Do we need to implement drag-to-reposition first, or is the undo/redo system only for future position editing?\",\n      \"category\": \"requirements\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"BayesNetGraph.tsx computes positions via layoutNodes() with no user interaction. If there's no way to change positions yet, building undo for position changes is premature unless drag support is also in scope.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q2\",\n      \"question\": \"For CPT probability edits, the current flow submits directly to the backend via useProbabilityEdit(). The task says 'before server submission' — should the undo/redo system intercept edits and batch them locally before a manual submit, or should it track already-submitted edits and reverse them with compensating API calls?\",\n      \"category\": \"requirements\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"This fundamentally changes the architecture. A local-only buffer requires a new 'draft/commit' flow in ConditionalEditor and VariableRow. Tracking submitted edits means the scope overlaps with server mutations despite the task saying 'server mutations are not reversible'.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q3\",\n      \"question\": \"What constitutes a 'layout change' that should be undoable? The current layout is auto-computed (circular/grid). Does this refer to switching between layout algorithms, or manual node repositioning, or zoom/pan state?\",\n      \"category\": \"requirements\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"The scope of 'layout changes' is ambiguous. Each interpretation requires different command types and state tracking.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q4\",\n      \"question\": \"Should the undo history persist across page navigations (e.g., leaving MarketDetail and returning), or is it ephemeral per component mount?\",\n      \"category\": \"design\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"Persistent history would require serialization to localStorage or session storage. Ephemeral history is simpler but users lose undo ability on navigation. This affects where HistoryContext is placed in the component tree.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q5\",\n      \"question\": \"Should evidence toggle (assumption add/remove) undo restore the exact previous assumption state, or just remove the last assumption? AssumptionContext.addAssumption() replaces any existing assumption on the same variable.\",\n      \"category\": \"design\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"If a user assumes outcome A, then assumes outcome B on the same variable, undoing should restore A (not just clear B). This requires capturing the previous state in the command, not just the action type.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q6\",\n      \"question\": \"Should undo/redo be scoped per-market (one history stack per MarketDetail) or global across the app?\",\n      \"category\": \"design\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"The AssumptionProvider is scoped to MarketDetail. If HistoryContext is also scoped there, each market gets its own stack. A global stack would need to track which market each action belongs to and handle cross-market interactions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q7\",\n      \"question\": \"Is there a maximum history depth, or should the stack grow unbounded?\",\n      \"category\": \"design\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"Unbounded history can consume significant memory, especially if commands store full state snapshots. A cap (e.g., 50 actions) keeps memory predictable and is standard UX.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q8\",\n      \"question\": \"Where should the toolbar buttons be placed? There's no existing graph toolbar component. Should they go in the MarketDetail header area, inline with BayesNetGraph, or as a floating overlay?\",\n      \"category\": \"codebase\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"MarketDetail currently has no toolbar section. The placement decision affects component hierarchy and whether a new GraphToolbar component is needed or if buttons integrate into an existing section.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q9\",\n      \"question\": \"Should Ctrl+Z/Ctrl+Shift+Z be active globally or only when the graph/market view is focused? The app has text inputs (account ID, agent ID, probability sliders) where Ctrl+Z has native browser meaning.\",\n      \"category\": \"design\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"Intercepting Ctrl+Z globally would break native undo in text inputs. The keyboard handler needs to distinguish between graph context and form input context to avoid hijacking browser behavior.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"q10\",\n      \"question\": \"Should grouped/compound actions (e.g., editing multiple probabilities in ConditionalEditor with context conditions) be undone as a single unit or individually?\",\n      \"category\": \"design\",\n      \"why_it_matters\": \"ConditionalEditor can submit an edit with multiple context conditions. If these are treated as atomic, one undo reverts everything. If granular, the user can partially undo which may leave the CPT in an inconsistent state.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"assumptions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"a1\",\n      \"assumption\": \"The undo/redo system uses the command pattern with execute/undo method pairs on each command object, rather than full state snapshots\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.85,\n      \"if_wrong\": \"State snapshot approach (e.g., using immer patches) would simplify implementation but increase memory usage and change the core data structure design\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"a2\",\n      \"assumption\": \"HistoryContext will be placed inside AssumptionProvider at the MarketDetail level, scoped per-market\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.8,\n      \"if_wrong\": \"A global history context would need to wrap the entire app in providers.tsx and track market IDs per action\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"a3\",\n      \"assumption\": \"Keyboard shortcuts should only fire when focus is not inside a text input, textarea, or contenteditable element\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.9,\n      \"if_wrong\": \"If shortcuts should always fire, native browser undo in form fields would break, causing a degraded editing experience\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"a4\",\n      \"assumption\": \"Evidence toggle undo means restoring the previous assumption state for that variable (not just clearing the current one)\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.75,\n      \"if_wrong\": \"Simpler implementation possible if undo just clears the assumption, but less useful UX\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"a5\",\n      \"assumption\": \"Node position changes and layout changes refer to future capabilities that need stub commands, since the graph is currently static with no user-driven positioning\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.6,\n      \"if_wrong\": \"If drag-to-reposition is expected to ship alongside undo/redo, the scope is significantly larger than described\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"a6\",\n      \"assumption\": \"History is ephemeral (cleared on unmount/navigation), not persisted to localStorage\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.7,\n      \"if_wrong\": \"Would need serialization/deserialization of command objects and localStorage management\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"a7\",\n      \"assumption\": \"A reasonable max history depth of 50 actions will be used\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.65,\n      \"if_wrong\": \"Unbounded history could cause memory issues; very small cap could frustrate power users\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"a8\",\n      \"assumption\": \"No new dependencies (like immer or zustand) need to be added — implementation uses React Context + useReducer\",\n      \"confidence\": 0.8,\n      \"if_wrong\": \"Adding a state management library would change the architectural approach and require dependency approval\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"spawn_children\": false,\n  \"children\": []\n}\n","numLines":118,"startLine":1,"totalLines":118}}}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SkHJyVBnkKDYhWZqamR7d9","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t{\n2\t  \"phase\": \"research\",\n3\t  \"answers\": [\n4\t    {\n5\t      \"question_id\": \"q1\",\n6\t      \"answer\": \"Node position changes should NOT be undoable for BayesNetGraph since it uses a static circular layout (layoutNodes() at BayesNetGraph.tsx:39-60) with no drag support. However, ForceDirectedGraph.tsx DOES have full drag support via D3 (lines 313-359) with fx/fy pinning during drag. If undo/redo applies to ForceDirectedGraph, drag-based repositioning is already implemented. For BayesNetGraph, position undo is premature — the layout is purely computed. The undo/redo system should target ForceDirectedGraph's drag interactions if node position changes are in scope, or defer position undo entirely since dragged positions reset when the force simulation releases (fx/fy set to null on drag end).\",\n7\t      \"confidence\": 0.85,\n8\t      \"evidence\": [\n9\t        \"frontend/src/features/graph/BayesNetGraph.tsx:39-60\",\n10\t        \"frontend/src/features/graph/ForceDirectedGraph.tsx:313-359\",\n11\t        \"frontend/src/features/graph/useForceGraph.ts:79-86\"\n12\t      ],\n13\t      \"uncertainty\": \"Whether the task intends undo/redo for ForceDirectedGraph drag interactions or only for BayesNetGraph. ForceDirectedGraph drag currently releases pinning on drag-end (fx=null, fy=null), so positions aren't persisted anyway.\"\n14\t    },\n15\t    {\n16\t      \"question_id\": \"q2\",\n17\t      \"answer\": \"The current flow submits edits immediately to the server — useProbabilityEdit() (hooks.ts:154-164) fires a POST to /v1/markets/{id}/orders/probability-edit and invalidates queries on success. There is no draft/commit pattern for probability edits. The AssumptionContext acts as a lightweight draft for assumptions/context but edits themselves are immediately committed. Given the task says 'server mutations are not reversible', the undo/redo system should intercept edits BEFORE submission and buffer them locally in a draft state. This requires a new draft/commit flow where edits are staged locally, undoable/redoable in the buffer, and only committed to the server on explicit user action. The alternative (compensating API calls) contradicts the stated scope.\",\n18\t      \"confidence\": 0.75,\n19\t      \"evidence\": [\n20\t        \"frontend/src/lib/query/hooks.ts:154-164\",\n21\t        \"frontend/src/lib/api/client.ts:200-213\",\n22\t        \"frontend/src/features/trading/ConditionalEditor.tsx:57-70\",\n23\t        \"frontend/src/features/assumptions/VariableRow.tsx:42-60\",\n24\t        \"frontend/src/features/assumptions/AssumptionContext.tsx:23-52\"\n25\t      ],\n26\t      \"uncertainty\": \"Whether 'before server submission' means a full draft buffer (staging edits locally) or simply allowing undo of the intent before the user clicks submit. The current submit is a single button press — there's no multi-step confirmation where undo would naturally fit in the existing flow.\"\n27\t    },\n28\t    {\n29\t      \"question_id\": \"q3\",\n30\t      \"answer\": \"In the current codebase, 'layout' has two meanings: (1) BayesNetGraph uses a static circular layout computed by layoutNodes() with no user interaction, and (2) ForceDirectedGraph uses a physics-based force-directed layout with D3 forces (charge:-300, link distance:120, collide:50). There is NO layout algorithm switching — each component uses exactly one algorithm. The comment 'Arrange in a circle for small N, grid for larger' in BayesNetGraph.tsx:40 suggests future intent but only circular is implemented. 'Layout changes' most likely refers to manual node repositioning via ForceDirectedGraph's drag behavior, NOT algorithm switching or zoom/pan state. Zoom/pan is handled by D3 zoom (ForceDirectedGraph.tsx:284-311) with double-click reset — this is view state, not graph state, and typically wouldn't be undoable.\",\n31\t      \"confidence\": 0.7,\n32\t      \"evidence\": [\n33\t        \"frontend/src/features/graph/BayesNetGraph.tsx:39-60\",\n34\t        \"frontend/src/features/graph/ForceDirectedGraph.tsx:284-311\",\n35\t        \"frontend/src/features/graph/ForceDirectedGraph.tsx:313-359\",\n36\t        \"frontend/src/features/graph/useForceGraph.ts:99-124\"\n37\t      ],\n38\t      \"uncertainty\": \"The term 'layout change' is ambiguous in the task description. It could mean algorithm switching (not implemented), manual repositioning (ForceDirectedGraph drag), or zoom/pan state. Without explicit requirements, this is a design decision.\"\n39\t    },\n40\t    {\n41\t      \"question_id\": \"q4\",\n42\t      \"answer\": \"History should be ephemeral per component mount. The AssumptionProvider is already scoped to MarketDetail (MarketDetail.tsx:54-56) and uses React state that resets on unmount. There is no localStorage persistence for assumptions. The only localStorage usage in the app is for session state (session/context.tsx). Implementing persistent undo history would require serializing command objects, which adds significant complexity (especially for commands referencing React state or API results). Given the app's current patterns, ephemeral history scoped to the MarketDetail mount lifecycle is the natural fit.\",\n43\t      \"confidence\": 0.85,\n44\t      \"evidence\": [\n45\t        \"frontend/src/routes/MarketDetail.tsx:54-56\",\n46\t        \"frontend/src/features/assumptions/AssumptionContext.tsx:23-52\",\n47\t        \"frontend/src/features/session/context.tsx:4-21\",\n48\t        \"frontend/src/app/providers.tsx:17-25\"\n49\t      ],\n50\t      \"uncertainty\": \"Whether users navigate between markets frequently enough that losing undo history is a real pain point. The current app is a single-market-at-a-time view.\"\n51\t    },\n52\t    {\n53\t      \"question_id\": \"q5\",\n54\t      \"answer\": \"Yes, undo should restore the exact previous assumption state. Looking at AssumptionContext.tsx:26-31, addAssumption() filters out any existing assumption with the same variableId then appends the new one. So if a user assumes outcome A, then assumes outcome B on the same variable, the A assumption is replaced. Undoing should restore A, not just clear B. The command pattern must capture the PREVIOUS state (the replaced assumption) in the command object at execute time, so undo can restore it. This is confirmed by the implementation: addAssumption replaces rather than toggles, so the previous value is lost unless explicitly captured.\",\n55\t      \"confidence\": 0.9,\n56\t      \"evidence\": [\n57\t        \"frontend/src/features/assumptions/AssumptionContext.tsx:26-31\",\n58\t        \"frontend/src/features/assumptions/AssumptionContext.tsx:33-35\",\n59\t        \"frontend/src/features/assumptions/VariableRow.tsx:30-40\"\n60\t      ],\n61\t      \"uncertainty\": \"None significant — the behavior is clear from the code. The command must store previousAssumption at execute time.\"\n62\t    },\n63\t    {\n64\t      \"question_id\": \"q6\",\n65\t      \"answer\": \"Undo/redo should be scoped per-market (one history stack per MarketDetail mount). The AssumptionProvider is already scoped to MarketDetail (lines 54-56), not global. The app's provider hierarchy is: QueryClientProvider > SessionProvider > RouterProvider (providers.tsx:17-25). There's no global state management beyond session and query cache. A per-market scope aligns with the existing architecture — each MarketDetail instance is independent. A global stack would require tracking market IDs per action and handling the complexity of cross-market undo in a single-market-at-a-time view, which adds no user value.\",\n66\t      \"confidence\": 0.9,\n67\t      \"evidence\": [\n68\t        \"frontend/src/routes/MarketDetail.tsx:54-56\",\n69\t        \"frontend/src/app/providers.tsx:17-25\",\n70\t        \"frontend/src/app/router.tsx:18\"\n71\t      ],\n72\t      \"uncertainty\": \"None significant — per-market scoping is clearly the right choice given the architecture.\"\n73\t    },\n74\t    {\n75\t      \"question_id\": \"q7\",\n76\t      \"answer\": \"A bounded history depth is appropriate. There's no existing pattern in the codebase to reference, but standard UX practice suggests 50-100 actions. Given that commands store state snapshots (previous assumption values, previous probabilities), memory is a concern. If the command pattern is used (storing only deltas/previous values), each command is small — an assumption command stores ~3 fields. A cap of 50 actions is reasonable and standard. The codebase uses no state management library that would provide built-in history limits.\",\n77\t      \"confidence\": 0.8,\n78\t      \"evidence\": [\n79\t        \"frontend/src/features/assumptions/AssumptionContext.tsx:3-8\"\n80\t      ],\n81\t      \"uncertainty\": \"The exact number is a design choice. 50 is reasonable but could be adjusted based on actual memory profiling.\"\n82\t    },\n83\t    {\n84\t      \"question_id\": \"q8\",\n85\t      \"answer\": \"BayesNetGraph already has a toolbar-like header area (BayesNetGraph.tsx:373-425) with Export/Import/Clear buttons and stats. This is the natural location to add undo/redo buttons alongside the existing controls. However, the task references the ForceDirectedGraph which has only a simple header (ForceDirectedGraph.tsx:397-407). The undo/redo buttons should be placed in whichever graph component's header area makes sense for the scope. Since undo/redo covers more than just graph edits (assumptions, probability edits), placing the buttons at the MarketDetail level — perhaps as a small floating toolbar or inline in the MarketDetail header area near the market title — would be more appropriate. No dedicated GraphToolbar component exists currently.\",\n86\t      \"confidence\": 0.7,\n87\t      \"evidence\": [\n88\t        \"frontend/src/features/graph/BayesNetGraph.tsx:373-425\",\n89\t        \"frontend/src/features/graph/ForceDirectedGraph.tsx:397-407\",\n90\t        \"frontend/src/routes/MarketDetail.tsx:34-44\"\n91\t      ],\n92\t      \"uncertainty\": \"Placement depends on whether undo/redo is graph-specific or market-wide. If market-wide, buttons should be in the MarketDetail header. If graph-only, they go in the graph toolbar.\"\n93\t    },\n94\t    {\n95\t      \"question_id\": \"q9\",\n96\t      \"answer\": \"Keyboard shortcuts must be context-aware and NOT fire when focus is inside text inputs. The codebase has multiple Ctrl+Z conflict points: (1) DiscussionThread.tsx:94 — textarea for comments, (2) CreateMarketForm.tsx:73,85 — title input and description textarea, (3) MarketList.tsx:133 — search input, (4) App.tsx:25-36 — Account ID and Agent ID inputs in the header. The keyboard handler must check event.target.tagName for INPUT/TEXTAREA/SELECT and skip if matched. Standard pattern: listen on document, check if activeElement is an input/textarea/contenteditable, and only fire undo/redo if not.\",\n97\t      \"confidence\": 0.95,\n98\t      \"evidence\": [\n99\t        \"frontend/src/features/market/DiscussionThread.tsx:94\",\n100\t        \"frontend/src/features/market/CreateMarketForm.tsx:73\",\n101\t        \"frontend/src/features/market/CreateMarketForm.tsx:85\",\n102\t        \"frontend/src/routes/MarketList.tsx:133\",\n103\t        \"frontend/src/app/App.tsx:25-36\"\n104\t      ],\n105\t      \"uncertainty\": \"None — this is a well-established pattern. The only question is whether to also check for contenteditable elements, but none exist in the current codebase.\"\n106\t    },\n107\t    {\n108\t      \"question_id\": \"q10\",\n109\t      \"answer\": \"Compound actions should be undone as a single atomic unit. ConditionalEditor.tsx:57-70 shows that a probability edit with multiple context conditions is submitted as a single mutation with one idempotencyKey. CptPanel.tsx:42-66 similarly submits one edit per cell interaction. Since each user 'submit' action produces exactly one API call with one payload, the natural undo granularity is one command per submit action. Partially undoing context conditions within a single edit would be confusing and could leave the CPT in an inconsistent state. The command pattern naturally supports this — each execute() call corresponds to one user action.\",\n110\t      \"confidence\": 0.9,\n111\t      \"evidence\": [\n112\t        \"frontend/src/features/trading/ConditionalEditor.tsx:57-70\",\n113\t        \"frontend/src/features/trading/CptPanel.tsx:42-66\",\n114\t        \"frontend/src/features/assumptions/VariableRow.tsx:42-60\"\n115\t      ],\n116\t      \"uncertainty\": \"Whether there are scenarios where batch operations (e.g., clearing all assumptions via clearAll()) should be treated differently. clearAll() removes all assumptions at once — should undo restore all of them or just the last one?\"\n117\t    }\n118\t  ],\n119\t  \"assumption_checks\": [\n120\t    {\n121\t      \"assumption_id\": \"a1\",\n122\t      \"verdict\": \"CORRECT\",\n123\t      \"confidence\": 0.85,\n124\t      \"impact\": \"Command pattern with execute/undo pairs is the right approach. Each command stores the previous state needed for undo (e.g., previous assumption for a variable). Full state snapshots would be wasteful since most commands affect a small portion of state.\"\n125\t    },\n126\t    {\n127\t      \"assumption_id\": \"a2\",\n128\t      \"verdict\": \"CORRECT\",\n129\t      \"confidence\": 0.9,\n130\t      \"impact\": \"AssumptionProvider is already scoped to MarketDetail (lines 54-56). HistoryContext should wrap at the same level or just above it within MarketDetail. However, note that AssumptionProvider currently only wraps AssumptionPanel — HistoryContext needs to wrap more components (CptPanel, EventTradePanel, graph) if those edits are also undoable. This may require restructuring the provider scope in MarketDetail.\"\n131\t    },\n132\t    {\n133\t      \"assumption_id\": \